description: Brevet Major General Irving Hale - Camp Hale was named after Brevet Major General Irving Hale. Irving Hale was born in North Bloomfield, NY, 1861. When he was five, his family moved to Colorado, crossing the plains by mule team in a wagon train. He attended East High School, then West Point in New York where he graduated 1st in his class in 1884. Hale commanded and fought with the 1st Colorado Regiment of U.S. Volunteers in the Philippines. An Electrical Engineer by profession, he became manager of General Electric Company in Denver. Hale was a prominent citizen, engineered the first trolley line, and was one of the founders of the VFW. He died in Denver on July 26, 1930 and is buried at Fairmount Cemetery.

description: Tabor Opera House-stage, Leadville- Interior view of Leadville, Colorado's Tabor Opera House stage on opening night, November 20, 1879. The first show was "The Serious Family," a Jack S. Langrishe production. In the foreground are Andrew' ornate cast iron and upholstered opera chairs and a piano with sheet music. Proscenium boxes with lambrequins, lace curtains and gas chandeliers are on either side of the stage. An ornate frescoed ceiling near the stage includes a painting of cherubs, flowers and ribbons. The set includes a painted flat with three arches, several pieces of furniture, framed paintings, a taxidermied leopard, and a portrait of Horace Tabor on an easel at stage right. Tabor contracted J. description: 1904 Graduating Class of Leadville High School: The Graduating Class of 1904 was comprised of: Margaret M. Burns, Blanche F. Crispell, Jake Harwitz, Ralph S. Heath, D. Harold Hoffman, Agnes Regina McMahon, Harry G. Miller, Grace E. Owens (Valedictorian) , Frank H. Penberthy, Charles L. Poston (Salutatorian), P.B. Edson Skiff.The Class of 1904 graduated June 10, 1904 at the Elks' Opera House. The class motto was "'Tis not what man does which exalts him, but what man would do." Their class colors were old gold and black, and the class flower was the yellow rose.
